<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100602485432990></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100602485432990><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100602485432990>RE: Spell gem management</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100602485432990#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=97944><span id=Scholar>harrije</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>18 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Nov 17th 2:20 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I don't have a given 'set' gem arrangement, mostly because I'm getting to a point where I need to do a custom gem arrangement on a fight by fight basis.<br><br>That said, this is my general setup for experience hunting:<br><br>1) Fire-based nuke<br>2) Magic-based nuke<br>3) Malaise, or most current version<br>4) Conjure pet/Summon Companion/Buff swap spot<br>5) Damage Shield/Pet Heal<br>6) Expedience<br>7) Burnout<br>8) Gate<br><br>I usually only use the pet heal with my fire pet, so it's convenient to swap that out with my DS if soloing. If grouping, the pet hardly ever needs a heal anyway.<br><br>Even when grouped, and even on no-pet raids, I still always have a pet spell memorized. If the party's going south in a hurry, I'm going down fighting. During downtime, I use that same gem spot to cycle in my personal buff spells.<br><br>On raid encounters, I use slot 8 for making mod rods, or miscellaneous items (arrows, food, light sources, etc). On many raids, if you gate out, you're out to stay. If you die fighting, you'll at least get rezzed back into the action. When experience hunting, though, this slot is ALWAYS reserved for gate.<br><br>Lastly, the three combat gems at the top are changeable depending on circumstances. In Burning Woods, for instance, I might use my latest Anti-Summon spell in place of the fire nuke. In some situations, I might swap out one or three slots for rains, magic-DoTs, etc., just depending on what I think will work best, and what might be fun to try.<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
